Regarding the “class” issue, I’m honestly disappointed by the misunderstanding.
Our agents generally operate in two modes when generating or editing solutions:

1. Step-by-step tool calling for partial fixes.
2. Direct solution generation through full-context LLM inference.

From my analysis, the step-by-step tool-calling approach works well for function-based code, but not for class-structured problems. Partial edits inside classes often caused new bugs because the LLM only had a limited view of the code context.

That’s why I designed the Fix_task_solve_workflow to handle function-based code, but intentionally excluded class-based codes from this process, to prevent self-generated bugs and improve stability because our current partial workflow by tool calling was mading self bugs due to its limited context.

Ok so the way i see it theres two big problems: 
1. LLM variance, where sometimes it gets it right sometimes it gets it wrong. In a sense this is baked into the incentive, becuase we run the agent on the same 50 problesm ~4 times, but still a problem. 
2. Bias towards the dataset - a lot of labs are training on the benchmarks, so that when they release they can tout how well an model did on the benchmark (when really its a bit overfit). We saw this with agents that tried to coax the answer from the model from memory. This is a problem thats remedied by two things - include newer and more datasets (swe bench pro, polyglot, etc). we're also planning on considering user data (with consent ofc) to create a new benchmark, and changing it over tiem as more usage comes in. Hard to train on a benchmark that isnt out and changes every other week

hallucinations are part of what teh agent solves for, as well as managing context etc - if your agent hallucinates youll just get less problems right, and so the competition naturally weeds it out over time (when scores are lower there are easier things to optimize, but as scores go up you have to work on more complex stuff to keep your edge and emission)
